---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Highlight from "../../components/Highlight.astro";
import FeatureCollection from "../../layouts/FeatureCollection.astro";
import Feature from "../../components/Feature.astro";
import Heading from "../../components/Heading.astro";
import Paragraph from "../../components/Paragraph.astro";
import PageHeader from "../../components/PageHeader.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import ImageStep5 from "../../images/portfolio/elevator/step5.png";
import ImageStep6 from "../../images/portfolio/elevator/step6.png";
import ImageStep7a from "../../images/portfolio/elevator/step7a.png";
import ImageStep7b from "../../images/portfolio/elevator/step7b.png";
import ImageStep8 from "../../images/portfolio/elevator/step8.png";
import ImageWrapper from "../../components/ImageWrapper.astro";
import HorizontalScrollList from "../../layouts/HorizontalScrollList.astro";
import HorizontalScrollItem from "../../layouts/HorizontalScrollItem.astro";
import TextContainer from "../../layouts/TextContainer.astro";
import BackToPortfolio from "../../components/BackToPortfolio.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <BackToPortfolio />
  <PageHeader heading="Ideal Elevator Experience">
    I was once given the task to design the ideal elevator experience, as part
    of a job interview. In this case study, I walk you through my user-centered
    design process for tackling such design challenges.
  </PageHeader>
  <TextContainer>
    <Heading as="h2" step="1">Research</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      My first step was to learn more about elevators and people’s experiences
      with them.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Interview users" icon="qa">
          I interviewed 9 people about their experiences with elevators. They
          mentioned 30 different things they disliked about them, such as social
          awkwardness and dirty, cramped interiors. However, waiting for the
          elevator was by far their biggest complaint.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Research Elevators" icon="upDown">
          I read around 20 articles about elevators and learned many interesting
          things. For instance, it’s a myth that all close-door buttons don’t
          work. The main insight, though, was that elevator experts agree that
          waiting is the thing that people dislike most about elevators.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Research psychology of waiting" icon="hourglass">
          I read up on the psychology of waiting. I learned that many factors
          influence our perception of waiting time. For instance, waiting time
          seems longer when we don’t know how long it’ll be, what is causing it,
          or when it’s perceived as unfair.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="2">Requirements & Constraints</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I created extra requirements and constraints, to give the project a
      clearer focus.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Client" icon="mitsubishi">
          My client is Mitsubishi, one of the world's largest elevator
          manufacturers. The elevator speed race is over, so Mitsubishi wants to
          differentiate its elevators by offering a better overall experience.
          They plan to install and test a prototype in a 12 story luxury
          residential apartment building.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="User groups" icon="groups">
          Residential elevators are used by different groups of people, such as
          guests of residents, janitors, and maintenance personnel. However, the
          main user group are residents. These can be people of any age and some
          may have sensory, motor, or other disabilities.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Physical and technical constraints" icon="lock">
          The elevator should work in luxury residential buildings with 4 to 12
          floors, in any country around the world, and use the "collective
          control" algorithm. In short, that means the elevator will only switch
          direction when requests to continue in the current direction have been
          exhausted.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="3">Problem statement</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I distilled my research, requirements and constraints into a concise
      problem statement.
    </Paragraph>
    <blockquote>
      Improve the elevator experience of residents of 4 to 12 story luxury
      apartment buildings by reducing perceived waiting time.
    </blockquote>
    <Heading as="h2" step="4">Use Research Insights</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I used what I had learned about elevators and the psychology of waiting,
      to come up with various features that would reduce perceived waiting time.
    </Paragraph>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Speed" icon="speed">
          The elevator will travel up at 83 km/h (above which people get sick)
          and down at 36 km/h (above which people experience the sensation of
          falling). This will reduce both actual and perceived waiting time.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Mirrors" icon="mirror">
          The shaft doors will feature mirrors. Occupied time feels shorter and
          people have a natural tendency to check their personal appearance.
          This is one of the oldest tricks to reduce perceived elevator waiting
          time.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Time" icon="time">
          Computer screens will be installed behind the semi-transparent mirrors
          on the shaft doors. One door will display the current time, since
          people overestimate waiting time and clocks counteract this tendency.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Weather" icon="sun">
          Weather information will be shown on the other shaft door. This can be
          effective, since residents may be on their way out and information
          relevant to a waiting setting reduces perceived waiting time. It may
          also start conversations, which enhances the feeling of being part of
          a group, and waiting in a group feels shorter than waiting alone.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Color" icon="paint">
          Warm colors increase perceived waiting time, while cool colors have
          the opposite effect. Therefore, the waiting area will be painted in a
          cool color, such as blue.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Light" icon="lightbulb">
          High light levels increase perceived waiting time, while low light
          levels have the opposite effect. Therefore, the waiting area will be
          dimly lit.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Scent" icon="air">
          Certain fragrances, such as lavender and nutmeg, have been found to
          reduce anxiety and anxiety increases perceived waiting time.
          Therefore, a scent diffuser will emit a low-concentration blend of
          such fragrances.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Accessibility" icon="accessibility">
          The call buttons will be placed low enough for people in wheelchairs
          (and children) to reach them. They will also give tactile feedback and
          feature braille to facilitate use by visually impaired people. Lastly,
          a voice UI will announce the current floor, the location of the
          elevator, the direction in which it is traveling, and at which floors
          it is going to stop.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="5">Explore Visual UI Concepts</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      The elevator will also feature a visual UI. This UI will communicate the
      same information as the voice UI to sighted and hearing impaired
      residents. Perceived waiting time will be reduced, since the UI will
      explain why the elevator has not yet arrived at the current floor.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      I sketched various concepts to explore both what to show and how to show
      it. This made me more aware of the choices I had to make, such as the ones
      shown here.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep5}
        alt="Sketches of elevator UI concepts with different layouts and indicators for the floors and elevator direction."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <HorizontalScrollList>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Orientation" icon="upDown">
          Should the UI be vertical or horizontal? Vertical matches the
          elevator’s axis of movement. However, a horizontal UI can be placed
          above the elevator doors, which enhances visibility.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Floor indicator" icon="number">
          Should floors be indicated with numbers or shapes? Numbers are more
          informative, but can lead to cultural challenges. For instance, some
          countries use 0 for the ground floor, while others use 1. Also, some
          countries don’t use certain “unlucky” floor numbers.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
      <HorizontalScrollItem>
        <Highlight title="Cause of stop" icon="stop">
          Should the UI show whether stops are due to passenger pickup or drop
          off? Waiting time is perceived as shorter, when people know the cause.
          On the other hand, this information might create excessive visual
          clutter.
        </Highlight>
      </HorizontalScrollItem>
    </HorizontalScrollList>
    <Heading as="h2" step="6">Create Hi-Fi Mockups</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I created various iterations of high-fidelity mockups, after having
      settled on only showing:
    </Paragraph>
    <FeatureCollection>
      <Feature icon="person">The floor the user is on</Feature>
      <Feature icon="number">The floor the elevator is on</Feature>
      <Feature icon="stop">The floors the elevator will stop on</Feature>
      <Feature icon="upDown">The direction of the elevator</Feature>
    </FeatureCollection>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep6}
        alt="Six high-fidelity mockups of horizontal elevator UI concepts with different floor and elevator direction indicators."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h2" step="7">User Tests and Iteration</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I tested two high-fidelity mockups with users and iterated based on the
      test results.
    </Paragraph>
    <Heading as="h3">First round</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I showed the 2 concepts below to 3 participants. I asked them which floor
      the elevator was on, whether the elevator was going up or down, where the
      elevator was going to stop, and which floor they themselves were on. The
      top concept was easier to understand, but the elevator’s direction and
      participants’ floor were not clear to all.
    </Paragraph>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep7a}
        alt="Two high-fidelity elevator UI concepts. One has circle outlines around the floors the elevator will stop on and the floor the user is currently on is contained within a filled circle. The other concept has two rows of floor numbers: one for the floors the elevator will pass and the other for the floors the elevator will stop on. It features a circle outline around the floor the user is on."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Heading as="h3">Second round</Heading>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep7b}
        alt="A single high-fidelity elevator UI concept. It has circle outlines around the floors the elevator will stop on. It also features a dot below the floor the user is currently on. Lastly, the current floor is shown in a filled circle within a circle outline with an arrow pointing in the elevator’s current direction."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
    <Paragraph>
      To address these issues, I created the new concept shown below. I
      performed the same user test with 4 new participants. This time, the
      elevator’s direction was obvious to all participants. It was still not
      clear to everyone which floor they were on, though. A different visual
      indicator and a floor number sign next to the elevator might resolve this
      issue.
    </Paragraph>
    <Heading as="h2" step="8">Final Result</Heading>
    <Paragraph>
      I combined the findings and insights from my research into the following
      recommended features:
    </Paragraph>
    <FeatureCollection>
      <Feature icon="speed">High speed elevator</Feature>
      <Feature icon="mirror">Semi-transparent mirrors</Feature>
      <Feature icon="sun">Weather info on mirror doors</Feature>
      <Feature icon="time">Display time on mirror doors</Feature>
      <Feature icon="paint">Cool paint color in waiting area</Feature>
      <Feature icon="lightbulb">Dim lighting in waiting area</Feature>
      <Feature icon="air">Anxiety-reducing fragrances</Feature>
      <Feature icon="blind">Low placed braille buttons</Feature>
      <Feature icon="mic">Voice UI</Feature>
    </FeatureCollection>
    <ImageWrapper>
      <Image
        src={ImageStep8}
        alt="A vector illustration of an elevator. There is a horizontal UI placed above the elevator doors. It shows the current floor, the floors the elevator will stop on, and the current floor the elevator is on and its direction. The elevator doors are reflective like mirrors and show the current weather and time. A large sign next to the elevator doors shows the current floor number. The elevator call buttons have braille text on them."
        width="800"
        densities={[2, 3, 4]}
      />
    </ImageWrapper>
  </TextContainer>
</BaseLayout>
